Acreds, Atringents, and harp Juices do well enough agree with Sweets but no others: Some of thee do take their names from Heat, being the uppermot, as Acreds, Bitters, ome from exuberant Cold, as Acids, Subacids, Auteers, Acerbs, or owre Juices; and others from moderate heat, as weet, vicid, fat and inipid, the firt two of thee inclining to Cold, the later two enjoying a better degree of heat:


And to conclude this, we may very well judge of the Juices in our Bodies, as we may oberve them in ripe Fruits which are weet and grateful to the palate, yet owre while green, and dry of conitence; afterwards this drynes leaving them, a ofter condition poeeth the fruit, and when this change happens, this owernes turns into harpnes, and this harpnes by time and maturity forgets its acidity and becomes weet. Thus alt and bitter things can no whit be allowed agreeable with weets, which are allowed our nourihers, for all Nutriment turns to Blood, and good Blood is hot, moit, and weet; and therefore that Sapour which is nearet in kin to the Blood, without all quetion mut be allowed mot proper for Nutriment;


and this brings me into Natures third Office, wherein we hall view her excellent Liquids and and Balamick Liquors, amongt which are reckoned Chyle, Blood, Animal Spirits, Nervous Juice, Lympha, Salival Flegm, Choler, Pancreatick Juice, Serum, Urine, and Sweat, they conducing towards our welfare, life, and motion.

                        What Lippitudo is.
                        Scleropthalmia, or Lippitudo, being ometimes een an Inflammation of the whole Eye, but chiefly in the Conjunction, with rednes, hardnes, pain and Rheum, ariing either from Contucon, extraordinary heat, or weaknes of ight, and a plentiful defluxion of Humours happening in young Children, and others who are troubled with a weak ight, may in a great meaure be allowed to bear a part with Strumous or Kings-Evil-Swellings, the Glandules in the Eye being Agents powerful enough to beget the ame;


and as a general remark hereof, I have generally oberved, That when ever this Humour hath met with any Obtruction, it generally and uually creates a hardnes and welling of the upper Lip; and this I preume alo is occaioned by ome mall paages derived from the Lachrymal Glandule ent thither. And when-ever uch who have thus been troubled have been toucht by the King, thee Swellings have very readily abated, and ome immediately upon the ame have been een to vanih. Beides this Scleropthalmia, there is alo another kind of Lippitudo, and this by the Greeks is called Poropthalmia, or Lippitudo Pruriginoa, ariing from alt harp Rheum falling down into the Eye, and both thee ometimes are een to meet together, the lat increaing the pain of the other.

This being finihed, His Majety having by my Lord Chamberlain, or in his abence the Vice-Chamberlain, and two other Nobles, brought up Linnen, and the Baon and Ewer to wah his Hands, He takes leave of the people, and they joyfully and thankfully do every one return home, praiing God and their good King; and when this method is apparent to all men, and carries in it the greatet truth imaginable, what man of Sene, Religion or Honety can there be, which hall dare to deny the truth and efficacy thereof, being both glorious and praie-worthy? conidering that the Liturgy ued therein is holy, the implicity and reverence of the Ceremonies thereof being performed with all decency, the peron who performs this being hereto contituted by a Divine permiion, performing it without any appearance of upertition;


the Author of the whole Work being the Holy Spirit, and this Gift ariing thence with both its ue and fruit. Here's nothing but Benediction, and Prayers for the recovery of the Sick, Impoition of Hands, and Contraction of Health, the ame Ceremony ued as is ued at Baptim, the putting over the Gold being but as a Sacred Gift and Pledge of His Charity. In the whole, there is nothing but God worhipped, Chrit venerated, and poor Chritians cured, without any Figments or Cheats of Black Arts, Invocations of Evil Spirits, Characters, or the like deluions, all which I hope may not come hort of an Englih Miracle. How therefore hould all true Englih-men, and Sons of the Church, adore, and have in high reverence that great Soveraign, who can give eae to the Dieaed, by his Touching uch as are not only depicable to view, but fetid to mell, who makes no difference, as I have already hewn, between Great and Small, Peer and Peaant, Delicate or Deformed? What therefore can there be which might not make the mot Ungrateful Man change his rude temper, and weeten


it with a better belief? Let all the World therefore admire our Englih Monarch, who can by His Salutiferous Gift ditribute Health and Comfort to all His dieaed Subjects, not performing this in corners, but in the publick view of all His Subjects, in his Royal Palace, and in places appointed for Divine Worhip, and in the Holy Sanctuary. And this I hope may be a convincing Argument enough againt any Gainayer or Dienter whatoever, who are neither kind to themelves, or civil to others.
